<article>

  <p>
    Mindfulness is not a softer mood layered on top of the day. It is not positive
    thinking, self-surveillance, or a brand for “being present.” It is the mind’s
    capacity not to lose track of what is already appearing — breath, pressure,
    tone, thought, the lean of craving — while it is still here. Miss that, and
    attention keeps elaborating. Catch it, and a different kind of work becomes
    possible.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Pali word is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    — often rendered mindfulness, though recollection and non-forgetting sit closer
    to the grain of the texts. On this site,
    <a href="/concepts/tanha/">craving</a>
    names the reach after feeling-tone;
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    names the knowing that can see the reach without becoming another commentary
    about it. Overthinking is frequently attention that never returns — vivid,
    busy, and somehow still lost.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Mindfulness Is Not</h2>

  <p>
    English has made mindfulness sound like calm itself. Apps promise a quieter
    self. Wellness language sells presence as a lifestyle accent. None of that is
    what the early discourses are pointing at. A mind can feel serene and still
    be absorbed in a story it has not noticed. A mind can feel agitated and still
    know agitation as agitation. Tone is not the measure.
  </p>

  <p>
    Nor is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    a sharper internal narrator. A cleaner theory of the hour is not yet knowing
    the hour as it unfolds — including thought arising as thought. Analysis can
    refine the commentary. Recollection interrupts ownership of it. Of course
    reflection has its place. The confusion is treating a polished monologue as
    the training itself.
  </p>

  <p>
    Self-surveillance misses in the other direction. Watching oneself in order to
    perform well, look mindful, or harvest a special state turns attention into
    another project of craving. The texts ask for interest without decoration and
    without flight — not for a private audit that never relaxes into what is given.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Sati Is</h2>

  <p>
    In the
    <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/">Satipaṭṭhāna Sutta</a>,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    is established through four domains: body, feeling-tone
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>),
    mind, and phenomena. The list is not a curriculum of exotic objects. It is a
    claim that the whole of ordinary experience can become the field of clear
    knowing. Posture shifts. Pleasant and unpleasant tone flash and fade. Moods
    color the hour. Hindrances and path factors appear as mental weather. Nothing
    in that field is too mundane to know.
  </p>

  <p>
    The refrain is practical:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    with clear comprehension, ardent, having set aside covetousness and grief with
    reference to the world. That is not blank watching. It is active interest —
    steady enough to return when the mind leaves, honest enough not to pretend the
    leaving did not happen. Eyes closed while carried by rehearsal is not a failed
    sit so much as an unrecognized one. The first genuine skill is catching a
    thought as a thought while it is still present.
  </p>

  <p>
    That catching does not require a blank screen. Thoughts themselves can be
    objects of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>.
    What costs is being carried by content while the body sits as if attention
    were elsewhere on purpose — planning, arguing, forecasting, without noticing
    the carrying. Knowing returns the thread. Losing it again is ordinary.
    Returning without a story is the training.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "This is the direct path for the purification of beings, for the surmounting
    of sorrow and lamentation, for the disappearance of pain and grief, for the
    attainment of the true way, for the realization of nibbāna — that is, the four
    establishments of mindfulness."
    <cite>— MN 10 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <hr>

  <h2>Yoniso Manasikāra — Wise Attention</h2>

  <p>
    Attention alone is not yet liberating.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">Sati</span>
    can watch the bait and still lean for it. The discourses pair clear knowing
    with another tilt:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="yoniso-manasikāra" data-en="wise / thorough attention">yoniso manasikāra</span>
    — wise, thorough, careful attention. Its opposite,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="ayoniso-manasikāra" data-en="unwise attention">ayoniso manasikāra</span>,
    is attention that feeds the wrong features of a situation: the lure without the
    drawback, the insult without the condition, the story without the seam where
    feeling-tone became craving. Same contact. Different food for the mind.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider an ordinary sting — a message, a tone of voice, a small slight. Unwise
    attention rehearses the offense, enlarges the self who was wronged, and keeps
    the heat warm. Wise attention does not deny the sting. It asks what is
    actually present: contact, unpleasant
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>,
    the lean of aversion, the invitation to proliferate. One tilt feeds the second
    arrow. The other makes the mechanism visible enough that
    <a href="/concepts/right-effort/">right effort</a>
    has somewhere to land. The same fork appears after pleasant contact: unwise
    attention hunts the next hit; wise attention sees tone, reach, and the cost of
    treating a fading pleasure as unfinished business.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is where the
    <a href="/suttas/kalama/">Kālāma Sutta</a>
    meets usable practice. Free inquiry is not free preference. It is inspection of
    what a way of attending does to greed, hatred, and delusion. Wise attention is
    that inspection made continuous: not waiting for a finished cosmology, but
    noticing which tilt thickens
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
    and which thins it. Notes, not conclusions — and still decisive enough to change
    what the mind feeds next.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Sati and the Path</h2>

  <p>
    On the
    <a href="/concepts/eightfold-path/">Noble Eightfold Path</a>,
    right mindfulness is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sammā-sati" data-en="right mindfulness">sammā-sati</span>
    — the seventh factor. The “right” matters. Bare noticing without orientation can
    still reinforce habit. Mindfulness informed by right view sees body, tone, mind,
    and phenomena in service of ending the causes of suffering, not merely collecting
    experiences of awareness.
  </p>

  <p>
    Effort and unification depend on it.
    <a href="/concepts/right-effort/">Right effort</a>
    prevents, abandons, cultivates, and maintains — but only if what needs care is
    actually known.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="unification">Samādhi</span>
    deepens when attention stops scattering into every bait. The
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/">hindrances</a>
    are not defeated by willpower alone; they weaken when
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    recognizes them early enough that effort is not thrashing in the dark. This page
    is not the full
    <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/">satipaṭṭhāna</a>
    map. It is the quality those maps assume: not losing the thread.
  </p>

  <p>
    In the
    <a href="/guide/">guide</a>
    arc, this beat sits after craving and before
    <a href="/concepts/how-to-sit/">how to sit</a>
    — a definition of attention before the laboratory that trains it. The order is
    relative to the guide, not a requirement for reading. Cold arrivals still meet
    the same claim: without
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>,
    sitting becomes another place to elaborate unnoticed.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Into the Laboratory</h2>

  <p>
    Formal sitting gives
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    fewer exits for a while. That is why
    <a href="/concepts/how-to-sit/">how to sit</a>
    follows here: posture, timer, and return as a starting structure — not as the
    summit of the path. Later, the sixteen steps of
    <a href="/suttas/anapanasati/">āṇāpānasati</a>
    and the four foundations of
    <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/">satipaṭṭhāna</a>
    develop the same knowing across body, feeling, mind, and dhammas. Begin with
    returning. The maps can widen after the return is real.
  </p>

  <p>
    The day remains the larger field. Walking between tasks, hearing a tone change
    in a conversation, noticing the lean after pleasant contact —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    is not confined to the cushion. Wise attention decides, in those small seams,
    whether the mind feeds the bait or sees the condition. Nothing here pretends
    that seeing once settles the matter. The path is repetition with clearer
    interest.
  </p>

  <p>
    Recollection is quiet work. Keep the thread — and when it slips, take it up
    again without a performance review.
  </p>

</article>
